at|^^|cp||at|^a|
at|^^|cp||at|^aHere is Howard's feeling about support doubles. They are useful and help in Law of Total Tricks calculations since they differentiate between 3-card support and 4-card support. But you have to understand when they apply. They  can only be made by opener after responder has bid a new suit at the 1-level. And they can only be made when responder' is only promising a 4-card suit. So, for example, if the auction goes 1@c-P-1@s-2@h-dbl, that is a support double showing 3-card support in spades. Responder is only promising 4 spades. But if the auction goes 1@c-1@h-1@s-2@h-dbl, that is not a support double. Responder has promised a 5-card spade suit. Similarly if it goes 1@d-1@h-2@c-2@h-dbl, that is not a support double. The 2@c bid is not at the 1-level and it also promises a 5-card suit. So, bottom line is, if you understand when a double is a support double, they can be useful. I slightly favor playing them. But again, if you are playing with a partner who tends to forget conventions, I suggest you don't play them.|
